Wash and dry all produce except @green beans{6%ounce}. Bring @water{3/4%cup}, @veggie stock concentrate{1}, and a pinch of @salt{pinch} to a boil in a #small pot{}. Finely chop @cilantro{1/4%ounce}. Cut @lime{1} into wedges. Stir together @panko breadcrumbs{1/2%cup} and @Southwest spice blend{1%tablespoon} in a #shallow dish{} or #bowl{}. Season with @salt and @pepper.

Once stock is boiling, add @couscous{1/2%cup} to pot. Cover, then remove from heat. Let stand, covered, until liquid is absorbed and grains are tender.

Brush @tilapia{11%ounce} all over with 2 TBSP @sour cream{6%tablespoon} (1 pack). Season with @salt and @pepper. Dip each fillet into panko mixture, coating all over and pressing to adhere.

Heat a thin layer of @vegetable oil{2%tablespoon} in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat (we used 2 TBSP oil; use a #nonstick pan{} if you have one). Add tilapia to pan and cook until flesh is opaque and panko is golden brown, ~{4-5%minutes} per side.

While fish cooks, combine remaining sour cream, a squeeze of lime, and @chipotle powder{1%teaspoon} (to taste) in a #small bowl{}. Season with @salt and @pepper. Pierce green bean bag with a #fork{} and place on a #microwave-safe plate{}. Microwave on high for ~{3-4%minutes} (or until green beans are tender), then carefully remove green beans from bag.

Fluff couscous with a fork, then stir in half the cilantro and a squeeze of lime. Season with @salt and @pepper. Divide between plates, then place tilapia on top. Dollop with crema. Season green beans with @salt and @pepper and serve on the side. Sprinkle remaining cilantro over everything. Serve with any remaining lime wedges.